// go.work pins the multi-module layout for the
// `code-intelligence` repo so a single command rooted at
// the repo root can build, vet, and test packages that
// live under sibling Go modules:
//
//   - .                          (legacy `github.com/microsoft/clean-code`
//                                 module retained for godog feature files)
//   - services/clean-code        (Stage 10.3 owns; all new conformance
//                                 tests + recipes + DSL canon live here)
//   - services/agent-memory      (sibling service module)
//
// Without this workspace pin, a command like
//
//   go test ./services/clean-code/test/conformance/...
//
// invoked from the repo root fails with
//
//   directory prefix services\clean-code\test\conformance
//   does not contain main module or its selected dependencies
//
// because each `services/*` directory is its own module
// and the repo root's go.mod (`github.com/microsoft/clean-code`)
// does not enclose them. The Forge per-iter test gate runs
// from the repo root with the path-spec above; this
// workspace file is what makes that gate command runnable.
//
// The workspace `go 1.25.1` directive matches the highest
// required toolchain across the modules (services/clean-code
// pins 1.25.1; services/agent-memory pins 1.25.0; the root
// module pins 1.22.0 -- the workspace minimum is the max).
//
// Adding a new sibling module (e.g. `services/foo`) means
// appending a `./services/foo` entry to the `use` block
// below; no other repo-wide wiring is needed.
go 1.25.1

use (
	.
	./services/agent-memory
	./services/clean-code
)
